description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/app_identity/app_identity.c:273-290

size_t lichen_app_identity_copy_peers(
    struct lichen_app_identity_peer *out, size_t out_len)
{
    ...
    for (uint8_t i = 0U; i < ARRAY_SIZE(s_peers) && count < out_len; i++) {
        if (s_peers[i].used) {
            out[count++] = s_peers[i].peer;
        }
    }
    ...
    return count;
}

If there are more peers than out_len, the function fills the buffer and returns out_len. The caller cannot distinguish between 'exactly out_len peers exist' and 'at least out_len peers exist, possibly more'.

This forces callers to separately call lichen_app_identity_peer_count() to determine if truncation occurred, requiring two mutex lock/unlock cycles and creating a potential TOCTOU race between the count check and the copy.

Options to fix:
1. Return total count (even if > out_len) so caller knows if truncation occurred
2. Add an out parameter for total count
3. Return -ENOBUFS or similar if truncation occurs
